I can replace with `JsonDocument.Parse` to parse the stream directly and navigate the object hierarchy using `GetProperty` and `EnumerateObject`, which avoids the deserialization overhead since I'm just reading the structure anyway. But I need to check how `armProfile` is being accessed to make sure the property lookup works correctly. The rest of the properties stay the same since `element.EnumerateObject()` already handles them correctly. For the `ToString()` method on `ArmEnvironment`, I'm going to manually construct the JSON string rather than set up a serializer context, since the struct only has three simple properties to serialize. The `Uri` type should serialize fine with the default behavior since it just calls `ToString()`. Now I need to think through the `ArmClientBuilderExtensions` issue—the `RegisterClientFactory` method has attributes that make it incompatible with trimming and AOT because configuration binding fundamentally requires reflection.

For `ArmOperation.IsResource<T>()`, I'm looking at the constructor reflection calls and realizing I need to propagate the `[DynamicallyAccessedMembers]` attribute up through the call chain. The method uses reflection to check constructors, so `T` needs the appropriate metadata annotation, and that constraint needs to flow to the callers like `RehydrateAsync<T>` as well.

Now examining `GenericOperationSource<T>`, which is instantiated in `RehydrateAsync` and also performs reflection-based object creation. This class needs the same dynamic access annotations on its generic parameter since it's creating instances of `T` at runtime.

Continuing with the CreateResult method... I need to add the appropriate `DynamicallyAccessedMembers` attributes to handle both the public and non-public constructor requirements across these generic types. Since `RehydrateAsync<T>` calls both `ModelReaderWriter.Read` and `Activator.CreateInstance`, the type parameter needs to allow access to both public and non-public constructors. Let me also check if there's a synchronous `Rehydrate<T>` method that would have the same constraints.

